            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>“... to a man of a peculiar nobility and of all virtues but also of mindful justice ... and sincerity, and incomparable prudence ... praetorian prefect, patron, for the very many benefits brought to them by his foresight ... the people of Lepcis Magna, at public expense.”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>“...”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>“... a un uomo di peculiare nobilità e di ogni virtù ma anche di ponderata giustizia ... e sincerità e incomparabile prudenza ... prefetto del pretorio, patrono, per i plurimi benefici addotti loro dalla sua previdenza ... gli abitanti di Lepcis Magna, a spese pubbliche.”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text of the inscription, still in situ, has been erased so carefully that the name of the honorand is now completely illegible. The honorand, apparently victim of the damnatio memoriae, was praetorian prefect twice, probably (at least the second time) of Italy, Illyricum and Africa. The honorand was also the patron of Leptis Magna, whose people promoted the setting up of the base and of the relative statue.</p>
            </div>
